1 (2) An unlicensed guardian or an unlicensed conservator.
2 c. Develop policies and procedures for proceedings when a guardian or a
3 conservator is unable to fulfill the duties of a guardian or a conservator.
4 d. Keep accurate records of all financial transactions performed under this chapter
5 in the manner required by the office of management and budget.
6 e. Provide a report each biennium to the legislative management regarding the
7 operations of the office, including the cost of public guardians and public
8 conservators, and any other information requested by the legislative
9 management.
10 3. The office may:
11 a. Recommend rules applicable to a licensed guardian or a licensed conservator.
12 b. Grant licenses to a guardian or conservator and agency permits, including
13 revoking or suspending an agency permit.
14 c. Require insurance or bond coverage for a licensed guardian or a licensed
15 conservator as a condition for licensure.
16 d. Establish mandatory disclosure and reporting requirements for a licensed
17 guardian or a licensed conservator, including a process to disclose information or
18 submit reports to the office.
19 e. Provide training for guardians and conservators.
20 f. Monitor guardianship and conservatorship services.
21 g. Provide annual reports to the supreme court.
22 h. Distribute funding for direct payments, expense reimbursements, or other public
23 services, including funding for public administrators.
24 i. Establish and collect fees to support guardianship and conservatorship services
25 and the duties of the office, which must be deposited in the guardianship and
26 conservatorship support fund.
27 j. Seek and apply for private, federal, or other funds to help support guardians and
28 conservators and to safeguard the rights of individuals who receive public
29 services.
30 k. Accept private funds for deposit in the guardianship and conservatorship support
31 fund.
